{{footnote The Lands of Fal'Doren}}
\page
{{pageNumber,auto}}

{{wide
# The World of Rakkten
}}
#
The large world of **Rakkten** is Eons old. From grand heroes, to infamous villains, the world has seeen itself torn asunder and rebuilt again and again. Though conflict is ripe within the Lands of Rakkten, it's primary continent **Fal'Doren** is seemingly a bastion of hope amongst its denizens. Heroes have arisen from all walks of life, trained and untrained in the hopes of extingushing any whisper of evil from the lands.
<!--
While life has been relatively peaceful the last 1000 years, much has changed. Gods have risen to power, the world was forever changed, and rumors of a greater threat have emergered from the far reaches of the land. Before you can venture forth into this uncertain world, you must know of it's rich history and promise.
-->
The History of Fal'doren can be broken up into 3 distinct eras in the past Millennia: **The Emergence**, **The Plaguewinds**, and **The Fracture**. Currently, the land is in a new era, known only as the P.F. Era, or **Post-Fracture Era.**

## The Emergence
<!-- - The Time of prosperous growth for the many races of the world. Humans, Elves, Dwarves all rose in power together to help foster the modern civilization we have today. Other races soon followed, and it was a time of true peace.
  - Large cities began to be built, and **Atlas** Began Construction-->
  
A little over a thousand years ago, Humans, Dwarves, and Elves took it upon themselves to refine what is now known as our modern civilization. All three Major Races played a part in forging Fal'Doren into the continent it is today, with it's massive cities, beautiful landscapes, and rich history.

In 15 E.E. or "**Emergence Era**", Humans founded their first home; **Farendell**, a modest but relatively large city that was founded primarily as a fishing and agriculture center. It served as a stepping stone for other human clans to expand eastward and southward across what would later be called *The Lands Abound*. Over the following decades, they would create smaller settlements and as they began to reach the mountainous region of **The Shard Spires,** they found their first ally.

Elves are one of the oldest races on Rakkten, and the only that can sustain an extremely elongated lifespan. In 31 E.E. Humanity happened upon the great Elvish Captial of **Solstice**. A massive and intricate architecture of a city built within the trees of a great forest. The Elves were true masters of their craft, from their weaponry, to their homes, Elves found a way to prefer form over function, yet keep so much resiliency.

Dwarves on the other hand have kept their hardy nature in nearly everything they do. Originally living deep within the Mountains of the Shard Spires, the Dwarven clans united as a single front in 40 E.E. and have since been the pinacle of united civilization. While the Humans consistently war and disagree with one another; Elves being seperated by Class, House, and Nobility; Dwarves have combined their strengths to compliment each others weaknesses.

Eventually, Dwarves realized that the rest of the world would be fools to not put their differnces aside to join as one. As such, they invited Elves and Humans alike to join in the creation of the greatest test of a civilizaiton: A Single Capital of Fal'Doren. The Humans decided it would be called **Atlas**, the Common word for a large tome containing maps of a larger region. They believed it would be appropriate, stating that all others from across the lands would flock to the City. The Dwarves would utilize their mastercrafters in masonry to craft the halls of the city within the depths of the Shard Spires, and the Elves would provide their intricate designs to the courtyard and infrastructure of the city weaving beauty with functionality.

This unlikely union of peoples lead to one of the largest projects to ever be conceived, taking place over hundreds of years, with the "Official" end of the construction of Atlas taking place in 592 E.E. The city, however is still maintained and expanded upon in Modern Times regularly.
## The Plaguewinds
<!-- Drak'iseth -->
As the peaceful unity of Races continued in Fal'Doren, dark forces were beginning to form their own unified front. In the Year 694 E.E. a Black-Dragonborn Wizard, Drak'iseth, rose to power in an attempt to usurp the lands from the conjoined empire of Humans, Elves, and Dwarves. His dark magic brought about great Plagues and harsh unnatural storms that ravaged the lands. Soon after his rise, forests burned, oceans overflowed, mountains began to crumble. The peoples of the world were seperated, unity being a commodity of the past. All kingdoms began to fend for themsleves, not providing aid to one another, in an attempt to keep their own denizens alive. No lone groups of heroes could seemingly defeat his armies or onslaught, with any attempts swiftly cut down. With little hope remaining, a small band of heroes concocted a plan designed to decimate Drak'iseth, **<u>a death curse</u>**.

This death curse would sunder Drak'iseth's body, but not his soul. Although this troupe seemingly succeeded in their endevour, Drak'iseth manifested all of his remaining power to transfer his soul into one of his willing soldiers. This process was not fulproof though, with his body restored, his soul remained fractured; his mind seemingly undone. Drak'iseth's mind would warp and twist, making his misery he inflicted on others more vile and grotesque. Eventually he turned to murdering his own followers, and raising their mutilated corpses into mindless servants of undeath.

For the next five years, Drak'iseth's malefic regin grew. From targeted attacks on major cities, to bands of heroes being turned into his personal undead kill squads, there seemed to be nothing that could defeat even his lowest thralls. The world was at his mercy, and Drak'iseth was anything but merciful. However, in 700 E.E One Hero attempted to do what no other could: **<u>destroy the soul of Drak'iseth.</u>**
\page
{{pageNumber,auto}}

{{note
### Lonard Brakksben
Lonard Brakksben was a hero in his own right. Being the leader of the famed ***Thundersteps***, Lonard was a warrior of the Wilds like no other. Weilding a Longsword and Battle axe together, Lonard was one of the only known warriors to weild such weapons in tandem.

With his weapons **Lightning** and **Thunder**, Lonard procceded to assualt the armies of Drak'iseth firsthand. Starting his assault within the Jasper Wilds, Lonard cut down nearly any foe he came across. It was only a month into his retaliation against Drak'iseth that he made his way into the massive **Tarrleyan Forests**, where he began to ally himself with the druidic peoples of the foresets. With his own personal army aligned within the forces of nature, the druids rallied behind Lonard in an effort to cease the affront to the natural cycle of life and death.
:
Finally, it would be an ultimate assault against the forces of true evil. Within the reaches of the Shard Spires, Drak'iseth waited with his armies of the undead. The conflict would eventually erupt at the meeting point between the northern border of the Tarrleyan Forests and the southern border of the Shard Spires. The battle was unlike any other that had accured in history; Hundreds of Thousands perished in the conflict, with bodies forming mountains of flesh, and rivers of blood.

Standing above them however, were two entities engaged in seemingly endless combat, Lonard and Drak'iseth. Reports of the engagment were varied and unconfirmed, but rumors of a weeks-long endless frenzy was a commonality. Lonard struck with Lightning and Thunder, streaks of electricity slaying any foes who would stray too close, and booming waves of thunderous force flinging the perished away with ease.
:
Eventually, in a final effort to end the chaos, Lonard shouted to the heavens, beseeching the Gods to grant him the power to save the Lands and its people. Raising both his Greatsword and Greataxe above, he himself was struck by a single bolt of lightning and became empowered with the might of the storm. With this new found power, he began to overpower Drak'iseth, eventually forcing them both to succumb to the new strength he had been given.

The power of the Gods proved to be too much for Lonard's Mortal body to contain. As such, in his final strike against Drak'iseth, he too fell. But as Lonard fell the heavenes themselves opened, and granted Lonard's Soul a second chance: The chance to become one of them. Lonard would no longer be the mortal hero of Fal'Doren, but instead become **The Lord of Storms.**
}}

As Drak'iseths soul and life essence faded away, so too did his armies cease to exist. The corpses of the damned returned to the earth swiftly, leaving little left of the battles except for the living who had given their lives for the protection of the lands. After the long counting of the dead, the factions and kingdoms of the world agreed that the body of Lonard was to be preserved and buried in his final resting place, known today as **Lonard's Stand**.

## The Fracture
With the armies of Drak'iseth defeated, and a new Prime Diety secured into the patheon, the Lands of Fal'Doren began to flurish once again. For nearly two and a half centuries, peace filled the land. Temples and holy structures to Lonard began to take shape, and Cities across the Lands began to form new societies and factions of their own. 

At the forefront of one of those societies was a powerful Archmage, **Alistair Stormweaver**. In the year 885 E.E. Using his expertise in the arcane, he constructed a large Citadel deep in the forests of **The Wendaren Wilds** to house Adventureres from all paths of life. While Alistair himself was primarily a follower of The Lord of Storms, he wanted to create a bastiton for all Adventurers to flock to. His **Arcane Citadel** would become a massive enterprise, filling the Lands of Fal'Doren with highly trained and competent heroes. Alistair believed the world required a dedicated and good-aligned force to snuff out any forces of evil before they could  amass the type of power Drak'iseth had.

To his credit, Alistair's "experiment" worked. The Arcane Citadel produced some of the greatest heroes known in the Lands, and evil seemed to be put to rest very publicly in all parts of the world. Towns, Cities, and even Captials began to plainly show off iconography of the Citadel and its "**Arcanites**" in an attempt to show them safe haven, and as a warning to any would-be evildoers.

However, Alistair couldn't account for everything. For 115 years, the Citadel helped to protect the world from any threat that cames it way, but the greatest threat of all could never have been stopped. In what was supposed to be the "coming of a new age" in the year 1000 E.E the world changed forever.

The event know as **The Fracture** was one of unparalleled disaster. Historians recount it with poetic masochism; Scientists recount it as impossible; Religous Alcolytes recount it as a reckoning; But Adventurers, Adventurers recount it for what it was.
:
{{font-size:25px,font-family:MrEavesRemake **Disaster**}}
:
Records of what occured are vast and convoluted. The only certainties came in the massive changes in landscape. The **Tarrleyan Forests** vanished in the blink of an eye, leaving only desert landscapes as far as the eyecould see. The Northern Shard Spires crumbled and fell, blocking off the only access to the Ter'ak Sea from the Westward Shores, creating what would be known as **Horizon's Shadow**. In the Northlands, the Black Forest became cursed with Darkfae Creatures, morphing the forest into **The Blackwald**. Even the famous Human capital of **Farendell** saw pieces of its City disappear and other be replaced with impossible things. 
:
Finally, in the year 35 P.F. the world is vastly different...

\page
-->


