# The Miristar

The Miristar were once a secret ancient order of Keepers of Nature, but have since been wiped out. Since the time of **The Fracture** the world came to know of the exploits of the secretive Miristar. **The Tarrleyan Forests** were home to the Miristar before it seemingly vanished in the now vast **Tarrel Desert**. It's lush flora spanning the horizon even from the peaks of **Atlas** itself, many saw the Forests as the peak of nature itself, and those who cared for it were among the strongest and most dedicated Druids.

The Miristar's Order was not dissimilar to that of **The Arcance Citadel**, but whereas the Citadel operates in the light under the guise of a respectable order pursuing the preservation of Good and the extinction of Evil, the Miristar were the opposite side of the same coin.

The Miristar were an order of Good-Aligned peoples, that worked towards the preservation of the balance of nature and civilization, culling any threats to either society. In this way, the Miristar were excellent spies and infiltrators into many different Governments, Guilds, and Cults; finding the rot, and cutting it out.

However, since the near extinction of their people, the Miristar disbanded, revealing themselves in documents released to the public. The documents revealed that the original Miristar Order was in the near tens of thousands strong, but after the Fracture, were left with nearly less than 100 memebers. Since the order was so secretive, nearly all history or information shared together was done orally. In a final meeting of its remaining members, the Miristar realized their collective knowledge was miniscule in comparison to what they believed they knew, and as such, decided to disband and reveal the work they had done for the world.
::
Should any Players wish to join the Miristar, they would need to find a retired memeber, and convince them of their dedication to a now dead cause. Should the DM find this reason worthwhile, you can find your Group Patron information below.
## Ancient Being Perks
With the ancient being as your group’s patron, you gain the following perks.

#### Equipment
Your patron’s network has access to certain magic items. You can purchase common magic items from your patron contact. The DM determines the available stock or can call for a group Intelligence (Investigation) check to ascertain if the ancient being’s network can successfully locate a desired item. The DC for this check is 10 in a city, 15 in a town, and 20 in a village. If the check fails, 1d8 days must pass before the same item can be searched for again in that community.

The DM sets the price of a common magic item or determines it randomly: 2d4 × 10 gp, or half as much for a consumable item such as a potion or scroll.

#### Research
Relying on an ancient being’s network of contacts, the being’s vast collection of lore, or perhaps the being’s direct teaching helps you unearth hidden secrets. If you can contact your patron or their agents, your group makes ability checks made to research lore related to your patron’s interests and influence with advantage.

#### Sanctuary
Your patron’s agents have safe houses or other secure gatherings spread across a wide region. Your group knows how to locate these friendly enclaves and can maintain a modest lifestyle in one for no cost. In return, you must defend the sanctuary or protect the secret of its existence.

#### Strange Gifts
Your patron grants your group a small measure of esoteric power. At 5th level, and again at 13th, you gain one supernatural gift as described in the treasure chapter of the Dungeon Master’s Guide. The DM determines which supernatural gifts are available.

### Ancient Being Contact
The organizational contact who dispenses assignments or delivers the word of your patron runs the gamut from prosaic to otherworldly. Roll or pick from the Ancient Being Contact table to determine who or what conveys your patron’s will.

#### Visions
Your patron doesn’t use intermediaries, instead speaking to you in dreams, omens, or visions. The being appears in your mind as you sleep, taking control of your dreams to deliver instructions that become difficult to ignore.

![Miristar](https://github.com/PhantomDesk74/Homebrewery_Assets/blob/main/BookArt/Miristar.png?raw=true) {width:260px,mix-blend-mode:multiply}

